===============v1=======================
Don't return ORM objects - the session closes and the object is dead -> loaded attributes OK, lazy attributes - raises an Error 
 - flooding the system with backend = BAD
Don't create a new session pool in each store
 - use async_sessionmaker(expire_on_commit=False)
 - one overall session_maker all the stores use it
 - expire on commit - the object expire after commit, with sync OK a new connection is created when accessing the attribute
   in async BAD because it can't be awaited = raises error -> expire_on_commit=False
 - don't hardcode engine + password in one store
Don't put passwords etc. hardcoded into the code
 - use env variable and store it in .env file which is .gitignored
When deleting through ORM - SQLAlchemy - session.del()
 - I have to have cascade set if not - raises error
 - set it in the ORM object mapping

__init.py__ - needs to be in a directory to be a package
 - 1. mark a directory as a package - signal that we can do from app.storage import VectorStore
 - 2. runs when the module is first imported - package's constructor
 - 3. optionally controls package's public surface - where __all__ lives
 - import side effects - hard to reason -> if we put some code inside the __init__.py file
__all__ - what's public
 - list of strings naming the public symbols of a module/package
 - controls what `from package import *` pulls in
 - list of names this package chooses to expose as its public API
private things
 - leading `_` - convention only
CC's take on this session
Storage + embedding layer. 
 - Refactored the hand-written draft into subpackages (db/, models/, stores/, embeddings/). 
 - Fixed the Vector.id→chunk_id mismatch, moved DB creds to .env, shared one async engine (expire_on_commit=False), 
added cascades, Chunk.position, Document JSONB metadata, dim/length guards. Hard rule: no ORM objects cross a store boundary — stores speak DTOs. 
 - Learned: Python type hints aren't runtime contracts, and pgvector deserializes vectors back as numpy ndarray regardless of input, 
so reads need explicit float() coercion to honor list[float] (and to stay JSON-serializable).




TESTS:
 - pure logic (no infra) - 
    - chunking, promptbuilder
 - I/O seams
    - embedder, all three stores, retriver, llm client, ingest/query services, endpoints
- emebedder faked with a dummy constant = store, ingest
- real embedder in the retrieval tests - load once per test suite not once per test
- one test for the retrieval with hand placed vectors to test the distance/top-k logic in isolation from the model
- trunctuate the DB after tests so all start from deterministic DB state
